caption: I visited only because my best friend is named Henner and has a poster from the museum on his wall. The building itself is very interesting and worth seeing, though I'm not sure the collection and its descriptions do enough to justify a whole museum dedicated to this one artist. Still, you can see the whole exhibit in under an hour and learn about Henner and his contemporaries in less time than you'd stand in line at the Louvre.

Perfect example of paternalism: the female pupils of Henner were his clones. And their conservative art was totally out of touch with the modern world. At the same time, Impressionism was in full bloom, with talented, creative and free female painters: Berthe Morisot, Mary Cassatt, Marie Bracquemond, Eva Gonzales, Cecilia Beaux…. You can skip Musee Henner and his mediocre little repetitive talent, except if you are obsessed with red-hair nude models.
REALLY WONDERFUL!  Go read the timeline in the brightly lit garden room, and then enjoy the art. You only need an hour to see everything.
Very interesting small museum on 4 floors. Quiet on Sundays and closed on Tuesdays.

Quiet and not too crowded museum. The venue is more interesting than the paintings themselves. But it is my personal opinion. This workshop-type house has French ceiling and old wooden staircases which create a home-like atmosphere. A peculiar spot in Paris.
Great 'little' museum. It is a hidden gem. Well worth the visit, especially as it is not well known
Cute little museum, about a lesser known artist of the late 19th-early 20th century.
Quiet and interesting museum. The interiors are worth the visit.
Nice quiet museum. Just the arquitecture of it it's super cute. Really small so it's a nice stop if you want to do more things in the day. In an hour you have seen it all.
A small museum with a lot of, to me anyway, little known Henner’s art work. The house was also interesting as a glimpse into these large Parisian homes. It was very cheap!
Small but beautifully layed out museum, lovely staff too ! Would recommend a visit if you’re in the area
Hidden gem….. little known museum, atypical space with vast collection of Henners portraits. Worth the visits delightful concerts.

The museum reopened after a long period of renovation. The paintings and sketches of Henner are exquisite. While the museum space is small and the number of works displayed is relatively limited, there is a special atmosphere about this museum that lets you travel in time as if you were living in the "atelier" of Henner and watching him creating these paintings. The museum has also a rich cultural agenda of events that complements these wonderful paintings.

It's a small museum, but very interesting to see Jacques Henner's work. Besides his iconic work of red headed women the painting and drawings of his travels are very good and give a unique look into places of the past.  The museum itself has been owned by artists, so it is easy to imagine what it was like for a successful artist to live and paint in this private mansion. Easily you can pass an hour of enjoyment here.

This artist was considered one of the top impressionists of his day - but is now almost unknown. This house museum is interesting, but also reveals why his fame didn't last. Worth it if you're in the area, but not a top Paris highlight.

Okay if you are in the neighborhood. I was expecting more about life of Henner and more paintings. Of course, info would have been French only. Interesting house though. Not expensive to visit.  Nice park close by.
The people who work in the musée very polite and très gentile, although it's a small musée, mais j'amine beaucoup alot !
The building is great. You can get a joint ticket with musée Gustave Moreau it get a discount with a normal ticket front musée Gustave Moreau.
The woman at the counter had a terrible attitude
Beautiful building, free for under 26, feels like being in the home of this not so famous yet very talented painter! If you are tired of mai stream museums in Paris try swinging by this one!
A very secret treasure. A quiet and peaceful museum dedicated to a partly forgotten French painter.
A lesser known museum with an interesting location and worth the visit
Great museum, I enjoyed it. Definitely worth getting an audio guide.
It's a quick visit as the museum is small but it is interesting to see the inside of these old buildings.
Lovely museum and lovely architecture.
Very nice place and museum !
Beautiful and magical especially jardin d'hiver
Small, specialist museum in a very chic area.
Nice setting but paintings very ordinary.
Atmospheric, uncomplicated , unhurried  informative.
Nice cute little musuem
Cute and attractive small museum
Some interesting pieces in a nice setting.
Very interesting museum :)
Wonderful collection with English notes
